    },
    {
      "text": "Puyo Puyo (ぷよぷよ) is a 1991 puzzle video game developed and published by Compile for the MSX2. It is the first installment of the Puyo Puyo series, and uses characters from Compile's 1990 role-playing game Madō Monogatari. The game was produced by Compile founder Masamitsu \"Moo\" Niitani, who was inspired by certain elements from the Tetris and Dr. Mario series of games.\nThe game was released for the Famicom Disk System by Tokuma Shoten on the same day of the MSX2 release under the name Famimaga Disk Vol. 5: Puyo Puyo (ファミマガディスク Vol.5 ぷよぷよ, Famimaga Disuku Boryūmu Faibu: Puyo Puyo) and as part of the Famimaga Disk series. A year after the MSX2 and FDS versions, Sega released an arcade version that heavily expanded upon the original versions by including a one-player story mode and a two-player competitive mode.",
      "lang": "en",
      "source": "wikipedia_en"
    }
  ],
